80
00:05:12,689 --> 00:05:15,671
[SPEAKER_06]: And we'll move on to the report of the superintendent with the Mustang moment.

81
00:05:15,931 --> 00:05:16,432
[SPEAKER_06]: Dr. Galussi.

82
00:05:17,827 --> 00:05:18,247
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

83
00:05:18,307 --> 00:05:18,988
[SPEAKER_18]: Good evening.

84
00:05:19,148 --> 00:05:24,472
[SPEAKER_18]: So tonight we have students from our career technical education programs.

85
00:05:25,193 --> 00:05:33,359
[SPEAKER_18]: I know four are going to be highlighted but I'm going to ask director Fallon to come up and do a little overview and he can introduce the first students.

86
00:05:39,022 --> 00:05:39,542
[SPEAKER_19]: Good evening.

87
00:05:39,783 --> 00:05:40,903
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you for having us tonight.

88
00:05:40,944 --> 00:05:45,327
[SPEAKER_19]: It's my pleasure to highlight some accomplishments of some career technical education students tonight.

89
00:05:45,927 --> 00:05:49,170
[SPEAKER_19]: We have four seniors that are going to be graduating, and we have one junior.

90
00:05:49,510 --> 00:05:51,652
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'd like to start with the electrical students and their teacher.

91
00:06:02,408 --> 00:06:02,868
[SPEAKER_17]: Good evening.

92
00:06:03,989 --> 00:06:07,832
[SPEAKER_17]: Tonight I'm presenting to you Brody Sherblom and Cole McDermott.

93
00:06:08,272 --> 00:06:16,878
[SPEAKER_17]: Both of them have been students in our program since they were sophomores, and now they've been chosen to join the IBEW Local Union 103.

94
00:06:17,418 --> 00:06:21,942
[SPEAKER_17]: So they'll start their schooling in September, and they should have jobs by July.

95
00:06:21,962 --> 00:06:25,184
[SPEAKER_17]: They'll be making a boatload of money, and they'll be doing quite well.

96
00:06:25,764 --> 00:06:29,587
[SPEAKER_17]: So we just want to take a moment to congratulate them on a job well done.

97
00:06:40,207 --> 00:06:42,348
[SPEAKER_14]: I'd just like to say thank you to Mr. Cormier.

98
00:06:43,109 --> 00:06:45,110
[SPEAKER_14]: He's been a good teacher for the past three years.

99
00:06:48,012 --> 00:06:50,894
[SPEAKER_14]: He got me to where I am right now, so thank you.

100
00:06:52,054 --> 00:07:00,780
[SPEAKER_14]: Mr. Fallon, thank you for letting me into the electrical program, because I transferred from Arlington Catholic as a sophomore.

101
00:07:02,941 --> 00:07:08,244
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm very happy to start in June for the IBW 103.

102
00:07:13,458 --> 00:07:18,942
[SPEAKER_01]: I'd like to thank the same people as well, Mr. Cormier and Mr. Fallon, for the opportunities we have at the Volk.

103
00:07:19,282 --> 00:07:24,086
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm also very excited to start here in July for the union.

104
00:07:27,728 --> 00:07:33,172
[SPEAKER_19]: And I know it's about the students, but we do have a certain somebody who's retiring from the district after 29, 19 years.

105
00:07:37,113 --> 00:07:38,194
[SPEAKER_19]: How dare I?

106
00:07:38,454 --> 00:07:40,517
[SPEAKER_19]: Mr. Cormier is going to be leaving us at the end of June.

107
00:07:41,057 --> 00:07:46,303
[SPEAKER_19]: And I just want to publicly thank him for his service and dedication to the electrical program where he was once a student.

108
00:07:46,963 --> 00:07:52,569
[SPEAKER_19]: And I really appreciate what he's done for me when I came into Medford is not knowing much about the community.

109
00:07:52,629 --> 00:07:55,873
[SPEAKER_19]: He really helped kind of bring me into Medford.

110
00:07:55,893 --> 00:07:57,955
[SPEAKER_19]: So thank you, Mr. Cormier, and congratulations to you.

111
00:08:04,302 --> 00:08:07,344
[SPEAKER_19]: OK, our next student I'm going to bring up is from our biotechnology program.

112
00:08:07,644 --> 00:08:15,188
[SPEAKER_19]: Jaden Zhang was recognized at the Mass Association of Vocational Administrators for the Outstanding Student of the Year.

113
00:08:15,709 --> 00:08:20,371
[SPEAKER_19]: He is also our top-ranked CTE student this year, and he will be speaking at our graduation.

114
00:08:20,652 --> 00:08:20,872
[SPEAKER_19]: Jaden.

115
00:08:26,787 --> 00:08:27,087
[SPEAKER_15]: Hello.

116
00:08:28,088 --> 00:08:34,635
[SPEAKER_15]: I just wanted to talk about how I ended up getting here and the steps I took to reach where I am today.

117
00:08:34,655 --> 00:08:41,903
[SPEAKER_15]: I originally joined the CTE program because I wanted to explore different opportunities.

118
00:08:41,963 --> 00:08:44,706
[SPEAKER_15]: I didn't know what I'd do after high school.

119
00:08:45,769 --> 00:08:53,575
[SPEAKER_15]: And at first, I thought I would go into a shop like automotive or electrical, but as I got through the exploratories, I ended up choosing biotech.

120
00:08:54,376 --> 00:08:56,878
[SPEAKER_15]: And that's partly due to Mr. Rousseau.

121
00:08:57,078 --> 00:09:01,922
[SPEAKER_15]: He's my biotech teacher, and he's a really funny guy, and I like the way he teaches.

122
00:09:05,052 --> 00:09:22,625
[SPEAKER_15]: My other biotech teacher, Mr. Weigel, he helped push me to take a class at Bunker Hill, which I thought was a really nice experience because it helped me get to know what college would be like in the future, as well as just learn a few more things in biology.

123
00:09:22,645 --> 00:09:29,090
[SPEAKER_15]: Where will you be attending in the fall?

124
00:09:29,130 --> 00:09:33,794
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll be attending the UMass Boston Honors College in the fall, and I'll be majoring in biology.

125
00:09:41,573 --> 00:09:44,796
[SPEAKER_19]: And with us tonight, we have a junior student in the health assisting program.

126
00:09:46,118 --> 00:09:53,765
[SPEAKER_19]: She's gonna speak about her experience recently having completed all requirements and receiving her certification as a certified nursing assistant, Ms.

127
00:09:53,785 --> 00:09:54,446
[SPEAKER_19]: Hannah Maroof.

128
00:10:00,215 --> 00:10:00,936
[SPEAKER_13]: Um, hi.

129
00:10:01,837 --> 00:10:08,965
[SPEAKER_13]: I just wanted to say, um, like, thank you to Mr. Fallon and to Mr. Fimo and our new teacher, Miss Grover.

130
00:10:09,685 --> 00:10:12,889
[SPEAKER_13]: Um, I've been in shop since freshman year.

131
00:10:14,013 --> 00:10:23,140
[SPEAKER_13]: And I 1,000% did not think I was going to pick health assisting, because when I was little, I was always like, I'm going to cure cancer, and I'm going to be a doctor.

132
00:10:23,200 --> 00:10:28,203
[SPEAKER_13]: But being in the shop shows me that this is so hard.

133
00:10:28,544 --> 00:10:32,947
[SPEAKER_13]: Grace to everybody who is in the health care field, because it is a hard job.

134
00:10:33,467 --> 00:10:42,470
[SPEAKER_13]: And in shops, specifically, working on all of the completions you need in the hours for clinical definitely brought a lot of tears.

135
00:10:42,570 --> 00:10:53,874
[SPEAKER_13]: But it was so much fun because I get to experience everything in the real world that I would probably be doing in college as a 16-year-old in high school, which I believe is very amazing.

136
00:10:54,534 --> 00:11:01,176
[SPEAKER_13]: And we recently just took our CNA test, and we all pretty much got 100 flat on the skills exam.

137
00:11:01,436 --> 00:11:02,597
[SPEAKER_13]: So that was perfect.

138
00:11:07,463 --> 00:11:08,844
[SPEAKER_18]: I believe that's two years in a row, Mr. Fallon.

139
00:11:08,864 --> 00:11:12,445
[SPEAKER_19]: I was just going to say, not that we're keeping count, but that is 100% pass rate.

140
00:11:12,465 --> 00:11:14,906
[SPEAKER_19]: And the CNA test is a rigorous two-part exam.

141
00:11:14,946 --> 00:11:17,667
[SPEAKER_19]: It's a practical assessment and a written component.

142
00:11:18,327 --> 00:11:21,608
[SPEAKER_19]: And all students that have taken it up to this point this year have successfully passed.

143
00:11:22,148 --> 00:11:28,190
[SPEAKER_19]: These are just examples of many of the things that go on every day in our school, but it's nice to have a minute to highlight a few here tonight.

144
00:11:28,210 --> 00:11:29,171
[SPEAKER_19]: So thank you for having us.

145
00:11:30,811 --> 00:11:31,112
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you.

146
00:11:37,889 --> 00:11:41,832
[SPEAKER_06]: Are there any questions from the committee before we ask our students to come up and take a picture?

147
00:11:41,852 --> 00:11:46,335
[SPEAKER_06]: Did I see a question?

148
00:11:46,435 --> 00:11:47,916
[SPEAKER_06]: Erica, sorry, member Reinfeld.

149
00:11:48,136 --> 00:11:59,584
[SPEAKER_08]: So one comment, which is, so a couple of us attended the health career signing day at the school and everything you talked about was what the featured speakers talked about.

150
00:11:59,624 --> 00:12:01,065
[SPEAKER_08]: Were you at that ceremony as well?

151
00:12:03,847 --> 00:12:04,067
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

152
00:12:06,023 --> 00:12:09,140
[SPEAKER_08]: Excellent, yeah, so it was really encouraging to see.

153
00:12:10,389 --> 00:12:13,050
[SPEAKER_08]: that what you're doing in school is really mirroring it.

154
00:12:13,090 --> 00:12:15,411
[SPEAKER_08]: And I will say, I worked at a cancer center for 10 years.

155
00:12:16,051 --> 00:12:19,893
[SPEAKER_08]: And it takes a lot of people to find cures for cancer, right?

156
00:12:20,033 --> 00:12:21,013
[SPEAKER_08]: Everyone works together.

157
00:12:21,034 --> 00:12:23,014
[SPEAKER_08]: And that was one of the really wonderful things to see.

158
00:12:23,635 --> 00:12:36,400
[SPEAKER_08]: And then speaking of working together, I was wondering in the biotech program, when I toured it when I first joined the school committee, they were talking about the collaboration between the biotech and the auto mechanics.

159
00:12:36,620 --> 00:12:38,481
[SPEAKER_08]: Did you get a chance to participate in that?

160
00:12:39,743 --> 00:12:43,105
[SPEAKER_08]: Because I remember you just said, I thought maybe I do auto mechanics.

161
00:12:43,185 --> 00:12:46,247
[SPEAKER_08]: And I was really intrigued to hear how those were coming together.

162
00:12:46,848 --> 00:12:56,834
[SPEAKER_15]: So my year specifically, we didn't, we weren't a large part of it, but we were able to view like the go-kart we were working on.

163
00:12:56,854 --> 00:13:00,276
[SPEAKER_15]: We were trying to troubleshoot what happened to the engine after it failed.

164
00:13:01,017 --> 00:13:01,757
[SPEAKER_08]: Super important.

165
00:13:01,957 --> 00:13:02,158
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah.

166
00:13:05,239 --> 00:13:09,702
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, we were actually making biodiesel in our lab in order to fuel the go-kart.

167
00:13:10,763 --> 00:13:14,286
[SPEAKER_08]: So I just, I love seeing how everything kind of comes together in practice there.

168
00:13:14,326 --> 00:13:16,968
[SPEAKER_08]: So thank you for illustrating that and sharing your experience.

169
00:13:18,149 --> 00:13:19,349
[SPEAKER_08]: That's all for questions from me.

170
00:13:21,751 --> 00:13:23,032
[SPEAKER_06]: Any other questions, comments?

171
00:13:23,052 --> 00:13:32,259
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, if our students can come up, we love to take quick pictures to commemorate your presentations with us.

172
00:15:00,710 --> 00:15:02,553
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, on to item number two.

173
00:15:03,574 --> 00:15:07,320
[SPEAKER_06]: Recommendation to approve Medford Public Schools as a no school choice district.

174
00:15:07,681 --> 00:15:08,522
[SPEAKER_06]: Dr. Galussi.

175
00:15:08,542 --> 00:15:11,426
[SPEAKER_18]: Okay, thank you.

176
00:15:14,086 --> 00:15:26,654
[SPEAKER_18]: So tonight, we're here to present the formal recommendation regarding our district's participation in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts External School Choice Program for the upcoming 26-27 school year.

177
00:15:27,634 --> 00:15:38,621
[SPEAKER_18]: So under Massachusetts school law, every public school district is automatically mandated to participate in this external program and accept out-of-district students unless

178
00:15:39,441 --> 00:15:43,726
[SPEAKER_18]: the local school committee takes an official vote to opt out of the program.

179
00:15:44,467 --> 00:15:55,559
[SPEAKER_18]: Because of this framework, we must officially report the decision that's made here this evening to DESE, the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education, in June each year.

180
00:15:56,673 --> 00:16:06,081
[SPEAKER_18]: So just after careful consideration, we are here and looking at our operational capacity, our financial capacity.

181
00:16:06,642 --> 00:16:16,030
[SPEAKER_18]: It is the school district's recommendation that Medford Public School, excuse me, the Medford School Committee vote not to participate in the school choice program for next year.

182
00:16:17,071 --> 00:16:33,319
[SPEAKER_18]: By voting to opt out, we maintain a consistent historical position that Medford has held since this state program's inception, and our decision is rooted in operational and financial responsibility.

183
00:16:34,880 --> 00:16:37,541
[SPEAKER_18]: Just to capture a little bit, if you

184
00:16:38,439 --> 00:16:57,372
[SPEAKER_18]: remain in the program, the out-of-district students would receive a state baseline tuition, and these admissions also depend on availability that could introduce a little bit of an unexpected enrollment fluctuations across grade levels and or buildings.

185
00:16:59,673 --> 00:17:10,036
[SPEAKER_18]: Historically, we have opted out of this to maintain local efforts around maximizing our resources, our time, and our instructional focus for Medford residents.

186
00:17:10,116 --> 00:17:18,958
[SPEAKER_18]: And so therefore, we do recommend that we continue to opt out of the no school choice status.

187
00:17:19,999 --> 00:17:20,639
