01:22:11,215 --> 01:22:15,258
[SPEAKER_16]: our Wakefield Memorial High School project, and all the way back to our Waltham High School project.

881
01:22:15,698 --> 01:22:28,027
[SPEAKER_16]: And I think those consistently showed that the comments that Medford received were very much in line with comments that the MSBA has made consistently throughout at this stage of the project development.

882
01:22:28,427 --> 01:22:30,509
[SPEAKER_16]: So it was good to see that commonality.

883
01:22:30,569 --> 01:22:38,014
[SPEAKER_16]: And I also appreciated hearing Jenny's comments about the Salem High School comments being in alignment as well.

884
01:22:38,474 --> 01:22:44,435
[SPEAKER_16]: I think there's consistency in terms of how the MSBA is providing guidance and feedback here at this stage.

885
01:22:46,095 --> 01:22:46,315
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

886
01:22:46,415 --> 01:22:46,876
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

887
01:22:47,156 --> 01:22:55,757
[SPEAKER_04]: And then my second one with you all here on this, if you could confirm what my thinking would be in terms of the CM.

888
01:22:56,497 --> 01:22:58,738
[SPEAKER_04]: This is kind of to respond to you, Member Rousseau's.

889
01:23:00,678 --> 01:23:06,039
[SPEAKER_04]: The Article 97 and the CM at risk model would kind of be completely

890
01:23:06,595 --> 01:23:23,144
[SPEAKER_04]: at odds with each other because the CM at risk model coming in when there's so much unknown would really lead to a wildly out of touch costing from a CM at risk.

891
01:23:23,424 --> 01:23:33,150
[SPEAKER_04]: Would that be kind of your thought process or could they kind of help with that process in any way, shape or form if they came in earlier?

892
01:23:35,669 --> 01:23:38,070
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you mind if I respond to that, Member Graham?

893
01:23:39,610 --> 01:23:40,330
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, please do.

894
01:23:40,790 --> 01:23:41,090
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

895
01:23:41,930 --> 01:23:57,334
[SPEAKER_05]: So we would, at this stage, if the SBC does decide to move forward with an Article 97 process, that process would be, a timeline for that process would be built out.

896
01:23:57,414 --> 01:24:02,315
[SPEAKER_05]: We would, as Member Graham stated, we would be in close talks with the MSBA.

897
01:24:02,875 --> 01:24:04,537
[SPEAKER_05]: to make sure that timeline works out.

898
01:24:05,357 --> 01:24:11,943
[SPEAKER_05]: The article 97 process is at least a known concept and process that can be scheduled out.

899
01:24:12,043 --> 01:24:21,731
[SPEAKER_05]: It would not be the first project that we worked on that an article 97 process is happening while the CM is brought on during the

900
01:24:22,191 --> 01:24:24,772
[SPEAKER_05]: tail end of schematic design for our project.

901
01:24:24,832 --> 01:24:39,777
[SPEAKER_05]: In fact, it's helpful to get their early buy-in and involvement so that they can weigh in on things around logistics and phasing of some of that work.

902
01:24:40,497 --> 01:24:45,439
[SPEAKER_05]: And I'm sure SMMA, if you want to add to any color, I'm sure you've seen the same

903
01:24:47,357 --> 01:24:57,563
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, no, Jen, I think that's an accurate description of sort of the value that the CM can add as part of the process if they were to come on board now, but it could also go in the other direction as well.

904
01:24:57,583 --> 01:24:58,104
[SPEAKER_16]: And we could wait.

905
01:24:58,244 --> 01:25:02,706
[SPEAKER_16]: I think there's, we can be a little agnostic in terms of the CM at this point in the process.

906
01:25:04,387 --> 01:25:04,708
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

907
01:25:07,990 --> 01:25:10,951
[SPEAKER_06]: Are there any other questions from the committee?

908
01:25:11,232 --> 01:25:11,752
[SPEAKER_06]: Member Lopate?

909
01:25:13,236 --> 01:25:15,098
[SPEAKER_12]: Yes, it's more of a comment, actually.

910
01:25:15,819 --> 01:25:23,466
[SPEAKER_12]: I think, as members have mentioned, and I think I can agree that it's a deeply frustrating instance of this occurring, and I'd like to know more.

911
01:25:24,247 --> 01:25:34,377
[SPEAKER_12]: And I, as many have noted, like online, and Member Graham mentioned, you know, there's a spread of unintentional misinformation or just, you know, misunderstanding about what's going on because we're learning about it all in real time.

912
01:25:35,587 --> 01:25:43,033
[SPEAKER_12]: I just implore members of the community, members of the building committee, just anyone who's interested to reach out to our team to better understand what's going on.

913
01:25:43,093 --> 01:25:45,715
[SPEAKER_12]: We hold office hours, left field does on Fridays.

914
01:25:46,335 --> 01:25:49,758
[SPEAKER_12]: We have our community forum, our building community meetings, our school community meetings.

915
01:25:50,678 --> 01:25:54,881
[SPEAKER_12]: I just think it's a really important time, especially as we're going to move through this process and better understand what to do next.

916
01:25:55,262 --> 01:26:00,926
[SPEAKER_12]: It's in our best interest as a community to stay committed to this work because it's deeply important to all of us individually.

917
01:26:00,946 --> 01:26:03,227
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think as a collective, and I just don't want us

918
01:26:04,373 --> 01:26:11,319
[SPEAKER_12]: fall into our more negative attitudes, because I think that I'm feeling very frustrated just because this is very, very disappointing.

919
01:26:11,339 --> 01:26:16,343
[SPEAKER_12]: It's many years of work that we've been putting in, and to have it stalled like this is incredibly frustrating.

920
01:26:16,383 --> 01:26:19,686
[SPEAKER_12]: So I think I just ask that everyone stay together on this.

921
01:26:19,926 --> 01:26:20,627
[SPEAKER_12]: So thank you.

922
01:26:21,508 --> 01:26:22,268
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Member Lopatti.

923
01:26:22,308 --> 01:26:26,552
[SPEAKER_06]: Are there any other questions from the committee?

924
01:26:34,125 --> 01:26:40,047
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, all right, well, we will be moving on.

925
01:26:40,087 --> 01:26:43,248
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't have any continued business.

926
01:26:43,408 --> 01:26:47,930
[SPEAKER_06]: We do have one item of new business offered by myself and member Lopate.

927
01:26:49,230 --> 01:26:59,294
[SPEAKER_06]: Whereas the Medford Public Schools Project Transition Program serves students ages 18 to 22 with disabilities and is intended to prepare them for employment independence and full participation in adult life.

928
01:27:00,034 --> 01:27:08,861
[SPEAKER_06]: And whereas evidence-based transition practice shows access to meaningful community-based work experience is a key predictor of successful post-high school employment outcomes.

929
01:27:09,422 --> 01:27:16,688
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, therefore, be it resolved that the Medford School Committee request the superintendent and the administration to conduct a comprehensive assessment of the current

930
01:27:17,388 --> 01:27:23,073
[SPEAKER_06]: Project transition program and recommend improvements to assure alignment with best practices and transition services.

931
01:27:23,753 --> 01:27:33,121
[SPEAKER_06]: Be it further resolved that this assessment shall evaluate the program's effectiveness in providing community based real world work experiences, including pathways to paid and competitive employment.

932
01:27:33,681 --> 01:27:37,304
[SPEAKER_06]: Supporting individualized student needs and transition planning aligned with student goals.

933
01:27:37,885 --> 01:27:41,268
[SPEAKER_06]: Tracking data on placements, paid employment, and post exit outcomes.

934
01:27:41,888 --> 01:27:45,589
[SPEAKER_06]: Engaging students and families in planning and expectations.

935
01:27:46,669 --> 01:27:54,551
[SPEAKER_06]: Be it further resolved that the administration shall present its findings, recommendations, including any proposed programmatic staffing or resource changes to the school committee by December 2026.

936
01:27:55,831 --> 01:28:06,274
[SPEAKER_06]: And be it finally resolved that the Medford school committee affirms its commitment to ensuring all students in the project transition program leave with the skills and experience necessary to successfully enter the workforce and adult life.

937
01:28:08,952 --> 01:28:15,858
[SPEAKER_06]: Member Lopate and I have been working with some of our CPAC families for the last year or so.

938
01:28:16,658 --> 01:28:28,028
[SPEAKER_06]: I think we heard from them on the heels of the successful override and they are very interested in making sure that the students that CPAC represents are

939
01:28:28,668 --> 01:28:32,310
[SPEAKER_06]: sort of at the front of our mind when we're thinking about programming and that kind of thing.

940
01:28:32,350 --> 01:28:49,080
[SPEAKER_06]: And most recently they reached out to both of us to talk about project transitions and specifically wanting to understand how to advocate for an increase in opportunities for students in the project transition program specifically as it relates to employment opportunities.

941
01:28:50,320 --> 01:28:56,744
[SPEAKER_06]: So, Member Lopate and I had a brief conversation, but really this work belongs with the administration.

942
01:28:57,484 --> 01:29:11,491
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is sort of us trying to frame for you all the ask and the excitement of the community for support in investigating what's possible for our students here in Medford.

943
01:29:12,491 --> 01:29:13,812
[SPEAKER_06]: Member Lopate, did you want to say anything else?

944
01:29:14,472 --> 01:29:14,812
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you.

945
01:29:15,752 --> 01:29:22,294
[SPEAKER_12]: Yeah, to double on what Member Graham said, I think that one of the most important things in our community is our PAC groups across all the schools.

946
01:29:22,994 --> 01:29:27,916
[SPEAKER_12]: Our CPAC and our LPAC especially are the ones that I've taken a special working group, working attitude towards.

947
01:29:27,936 --> 01:29:33,117
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think that they've asked things of us, and I think it's really important that we're maintaining our commitment to them.

948
01:29:33,617 --> 01:29:37,318
[SPEAKER_12]: It's really challenging, especially when the services that their students and their

949
01:29:37,942 --> 01:29:41,804
[SPEAKER_12]: advocated individuals need aren't always as available to them as they would hope.

950
01:29:41,864 --> 01:29:50,928
[SPEAKER_12]: And so I think this was just a commitment to making sure that we're working towards properly securing those opportunities for these students to the best of our ability and understanding the pathways to doing that.

951
01:29:52,189 --> 01:30:00,873
[SPEAKER_12]: I think it's just something that we say we want to do and it's hard enough as is as a parent with students who have differing needs to find those opportunities because they're not always readily available.

952
01:30:00,913 --> 01:30:04,795
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think as a district we want to make that commitment and make them readily available, so.

953
01:30:17,152 --> 01:30:24,754
[SPEAKER_06]: I think we may have somebody in the waiting room of the Zoom that may want to speak on this issue.

954
01:30:25,335 --> 01:30:30,676
[SPEAKER_06]: So I just want to give her a minute to get signed in.

